## Independent verdict

**The `ms_used` accounting bug is real and is the right primary fix.** The trace story (370/400 `WRAP=1`, `numVerts‚âà74894`, `CuiLayerRenderer` locking the remainder) matches the code. The current tree already has the D3D9-faithful VB path in `Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp` (lock does not advance `ms_used`; unlock does).

**Two important corrections to the write-up:**

1. **‚ÄúDeferred draw‚Äù on the CPU is misleading.** `ShaderPrimitiveSorter::Phase::draw()` calls `prepareToDraw()` and then `draw()` back-to-back for each primitive (`ShaderPrimitiveSorter.cpp:725‚Äì781`). Skinned meshes lock/unlock the ring in `prepareToDraw`, bind VB/IB there (`SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:651‚Äì656`), and issue draws immediately in `draw()` (`:661‚Äì664`). The hazard is **CPU ahead of GPU** on a shared `D3D11_USAGE_DYNAMIC` ring, not recorded-but-not-submitted D3D11 command lists. RenderDoc replay looking clean fits that.

2. **D3D9 vs D3D11 bind semantics are not the differentiator for multi-stream skinned meshes.** With stream offsets, D3D9 also uses `byteOffset = getOffset() * vertexSize` and `ms_sliceFirstVertex = 0` (`Direct3d9.cpp:3855‚Äì3861`), same as D3D11 (`Direct3d11_VertexBufferVectorData.cpp:145`, `drawPartialIndexedTriangleList` with `baseIndex=0` at `Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:3263‚Äì3266`). Ground truth is the **ring lock/accounting**, not BaseVertexIndex vs IA byte offset.

---

## Q1 ‚Äî Why did D3D9-faithful accounting make D3D11 worse?

**Not because D3D9 accounting is wrong ‚Äî it is required.** D3D9 reference:

```216:244:src/engine/client/application/Direct3d9/src/win32/Direct3d9_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp
	m_numberOfVertices = numberOfVertices;
	m_offset = ms_used / vertexSize;

	return data;
// ...
	ms_used += length;
```

D3D11 now mirrors that (`Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:326‚Äì327`, `457‚Äì458`).

**What changed when accounting was fixed:**

| Before (buggy D3D11) | After (D3D9-faithful) |
|---|---|
| `lock()` charged the **requested** size (`~2 MB` for CuiLayer) | `lock()` only sets `m_offset`; `unlock(actual)` advances `ms_used` |
| `ms_used` instantly hit ring capacity ‚Üí **~371 mid-frame `WRITE_DISCARD`s/frame** | Trace: **0 mid-frame wraps in first 400 locks**, ~1 discard/frame |
| Most skinned slices effectively fought over **renamed offset-0** regions | **Many coexisting slices** in one 2 MB buffer via `WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE` |

So the regression is not ‚ÄúD3D9 math breaks D3D11.‚Äù It is: **fixing accounting removed pathological discards and exposed the normal D3D11 dynamic-ring rule: `WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE` is only safe if the driver knows the GPU has finished with everything below the new write point.** Under load, a cantina can accumulate a large foot-print of live slices in one buffer while the GPU is still chewing earlier subranges ‚Äî worse than sparse ‚Äúa few robe spikes.‚Äù

D3D9 uses the same `D3DLOCK_NOOVERWRITE` / `D3DLOCK_DISCARD` pattern (`Direct3d9_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:184‚Äì203`). It ‚Äúworks‚Äù because:

- Correct unlock accounting was always there, so CuiLayer never **virtually filled** the ring on lock (`CuiLayerRenderer.cpp:62‚Äì68` + D3D9 `unlock@244`).
- D3D9 drivers often stall/rename more aggressively on discard.
- Your **buggy D3D11 path was accidentally closer to ‚Äúdiscard every slice‚Äù** (bad accounting, fewer simultaneous live offsets), which can look *less broken* than one big contended ring.

**`P19_DISCARD_ONLY` does not exonerate the ring** (despite the contradictory comment at `Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:50`). Forcing discard every lock (`:279‚Äì280`) killing spikes but dropping hands is exactly ‚Äúonly one live rename region works reliably without sync‚Äù ‚Äî not proof the ring is innocent.

---

## Q2 ‚Äî Is the 2 MB ring just too small?

**Partly, but not as the main story after your trace.**

- With **buggy** accounting, the ring wasn‚Äôt full of real geometry; it was **full of fictional `ms_used`** from `CuiLayer`‚Äôs ‚Äúlock all remaining‚Äù (`CuiLayerRenderer.cpp:64‚Äì68`).
- With **correct** accounting, `WRAP=0` in the first 400 locks means those locks fit; you may still hit `ms_used + length > ms_size` later in the same frame (busy cantina, batch renderer, reticle, etc.).

When a **real** mid-frame wrap happens (`Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:288‚Äì299`), any draw still in flight against older slices can read renamed storage ‚Äî **unless you synchronize before `WRITE_DISCARD`**. That is the architectural issue, not ‚Äú2 MB is always too small.‚Äù

Reasonable architecture (in order of blast radius):

1. **D3D9-faithful VB accounting** (mandatory).
2. **Stop CuiLayer from treating the remainder as its reservation** (see Q3/Q4).
3. **`ID3D11DeviceContext::Flush()` (or a fence/query) immediately before mid-frame `WRITE_DISCARD`** when `ms_used + length > ms_size`.
4. Only if profiling still shows wraps: **larger ring** (`install()` tiers at `:139‚Äì142`) or a **dedicated UI dynamic buffer**.

Per-mesh dedicated dynamic VBs are overkill; the engine is explicitly designed around one shared ring (`Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.h:7‚Äì10`).

---

## Q3 ‚Äî Is `CuiLayerRenderer` compatible with the shared ring?

**Not as implemented for D3D11 with wrong accounting; with D3D9 accounting it is tolerable but still a bad citizen.**

The pattern at `CuiLayerRenderer.cpp:62‚Äì68`:

- Locks **`getNumberOfLockableDynamicVertices(false)`** ‚Üí essentially ‚Äúeverything left.‚Äù
- Keeps the buffer **mapped** from first `render()` (`:175‚Äì176`) until `flushRenderQueueQuads()` (`:528`).

On **D3D9**, that was OK because only **`unlock(s_numberOfVertices)`** advances `ms_used` ‚Äî the huge `lock(n)` is just the D3D9 `Lock` region size, not committed ring space.

On **old D3D11**, charging `ms_used` in `lock()` turned that into ‚Äúconsume the whole ring,‚Äù triggering the 371 discards/frame.

On **fixed D3D11**, CuiLayer no longer poisons `ms_used`, but it still:

- Uses **`length ‚âà entire tail`** in the wrap test (`Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:288`).
- Holds a **long-lived `Map`** while batching UI (`:306` ‚Äî only one subresource map allowed at a time).
- In **release**, there is **no** `ms_dynamicGlobalLocked` guard (`DynamicVertexBuffer.h:190‚Äì194` is `_DEBUG` only) ‚Äî nested dynamic locks during UI are undefined.

**Recommendation:** either cap batch size in `CuiLayerRenderer` or give UI its own dynamic buffer. You do **not** need to rewrite the whole UI renderer if you cap locks.

---

## Q4 ‚Äî Minimal correct fix

**Two changes, in order:**

### A. Keep D3D9-faithful VB accounting (already present)

`Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp`:

- `lock()`: set `m_offset`, return slice; **do not** advance `ms_used` (lines 326‚Äì341).
- `unlock(n)`: `ms_used = (m_offset + n) * vertexSize` (lines 449‚Äì458).

This matches D3D9 and fixes the CuiLayer amplifier.

### B. Cap `CuiLayerRenderer` lock size (the missing piece for ‚Äúfix made it worse‚Äù)

In `CuiLayerRenderer.cpp:62‚Äì68` and `:76‚Äì87`, replace ‚Äúlock all remaining‚Äù with a bounded batch, e.g.:

```cpp
static const int kMaxCuiBatchVerts = 4096; // tune; must be >= 128 fallback threshold
int const remaining = s_vertexBuffer->getNumberOfLockableDynamicVertices(false);
s_maxNumberOfVertices = (remaining < kMaxCuiBatchVerts) ? remaining : kMaxCuiBatchVerts;
if (s_maxNumberOfVertices < 128) {
    int const whole = s_vertexBuffer->getNumberOfLockableDynamicVertices(true);
    s_maxNumberOfVertices = (whole < kMaxCuiBatchVerts) ? whole : kMaxCuiBatchVerts;
}
s_vertexBuffer->lock(s_maxNumberOfVertices);
```

Existing `render()` already flushes when `s_numberOfVertices+4 > s_maxNumberOfVertices` (`:172‚Äì173`), so behavior stays batched without claiming ~74k verts for the wrap test or holding a gigantic logical reservation.

### C. Before real mid-frame discard (if wraps still happen after A+B)

In `Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:288‚Äì299`, before `mapType = D3D11_MAP_WRITE_DISCARD`:

```cpp
context->Flush(); // or fence/query when you have one
```

Only on the **true** `ms_used + length > ms_size` path, not on `ms_newFrame` frame-start discard (unless you measure that too).

---

## Attack summary (what I would *not* rubber-stamp)

| Claim | Verdict |
|---|---|
| CuiLayer + `ms_used` over-charge caused 371 wraps | **Confirmed** |
| Offset math / IA byte offset wrong | **Rejected** (trace `MISMATCH=0`; bind path consistent with D3D9) |
| CPU ‚Äúdeferred draws‚Äù with stale bind state | **Mostly rejected** (immediate prepare‚Üídraw) |
| D3D9-faithful accounting is wrong | **Rejected** |
| Accounting-only fix should ship alone | **Rejected** ‚Äî must cap CuiLayer and/or sync before discard |
| 2 MB ring alone is the root cause | **Incomplete** ‚Äî real fills + GPU lag + discard without flush |
| `P19_DISCARD_ONLY` exonerates ring | **Rejected** ‚Äî file contradicts itself (`:50` vs `:52‚Äì56`) |

---

## Bottom line

- **Root cause:** real ‚Äî D3D11 VB `ms_used` advanced on **lock** instead of **unlock**, incompatible with `CuiLayerRenderer`‚Äôs ‚Äúlock the rest of the ring‚Äù scratch pattern; D3D9 never had that bug.
- **Why worse after fix:** fixing accounting stopped fake discards and left a **large, correct, multi-slice `NO_OVERWRITE` frame** without CuiLayer cap and without GPU sync on any remaining mid-frame `DISCARD` ‚Äî a bigger hazard than occasional wrong-offset spikes.
- **Minimal ship set:** (A) D3D9 VB accounting + (B) cap CuiLayer batch + (C) `Flush()` before non-frame-start ring wrap if still needed.

I‚Äôm in Ask mode, so I can‚Äôt apply (B)/(C) in the repo; switch to Agent mode if you want those edits made and re-tested with `P19_RING_TRACE` on a cantina roam.
